WEBVTT

00:09.095 --> 00:10.565
[ bell rings ]

00:10.565 --> 00:13.202
[ crowd shouting,
punches landing ]

00:14.506 --> 00:16.577
LIBBY: A fair question
one could have is --

00:16.577 --> 00:19.617
how did our Toby Fleishman --
devoted friend,

00:19.617 --> 00:22.756
healer of the ill,
registered feminist ally --

00:22.756 --> 00:24.860
end up in
a Staten Island basement

00:24.860 --> 00:28.734
betting odds on a midnight
supermodel fight club?

00:29.703 --> 00:34.479
Well...after his breakdown
at the hospital,

00:34.479 --> 00:37.050
he was suddenly all cried out.

00:37.050 --> 00:39.088
[ mid-tempo music plays ]

00:39.088 --> 00:44.500
♪♪♪♪

00:44.500 --> 00:49.743
♪♪♪♪

00:49.743 --> 00:54.753
♪♪♪♪

00:54.753 --> 00:57.493
And in the vacuum
of the silence that remained,

00:57.493 --> 00:59.796
his loneliness became a void.

01:00.932 --> 01:04.540
Except instead of an absence,
it was a presence.

01:04.540 --> 01:08.815
♪♪♪♪

01:08.815 --> 01:13.056
♪♪♪♪

01:13.056 --> 01:17.532
♪♪♪♪

01:17.532 --> 01:18.568
Oh.

01:18.568 --> 01:20.270
[ horns honking in distance ]

01:24.813 --> 01:26.482
Oof.

01:27.819 --> 01:29.455
I hate this place.

01:29.455 --> 01:31.627
[ bed springs squeaking ]

01:31.627 --> 01:35.768
♪♪♪♪

01:35.768 --> 01:38.072
Even doing some of his
favorite activities

01:38.072 --> 01:39.643
didn't help.

01:42.849 --> 01:43.984
Excuse me, sir.

01:43.984 --> 01:45.087
Oh, hi, yeah.

01:45.087 --> 01:46.389
Um, can I get
the chopped salad --

01:46.389 --> 01:47.593
Yeah, I-I'm so sorry.

01:47.593 --> 01:48.761
Would you mind
moving to the bar?

01:48.761 --> 01:49.997
I have a party of four
waiting.

01:49.997 --> 01:51.533
Yeah, I ju-- um...

01:51.533 --> 01:53.269
I hate eating at the bar.

01:53.269 --> 01:55.306
Yeah, of course.
Sure.

01:57.178 --> 01:59.148
Thanks. Yeah, I can do it.
Thank you.

01:59.148 --> 02:01.118
Yeah, thanks.

02:01.118 --> 02:02.355
And you're sure I can't --
Yeah.

02:02.355 --> 02:04.860
Fine. Okay.

02:04.860 --> 02:06.129
Right this way.

02:06.129 --> 02:09.870
♪♪♪♪

02:09.870 --> 02:13.410
♪♪♪♪

02:13.410 --> 02:15.782
He tried going
to his favorite place.

02:15.782 --> 02:20.992
♪♪♪♪

02:20.992 --> 02:22.461
There was an exhibit there

02:22.461 --> 02:24.532
he'd been looking forward to
all summer.

02:26.637 --> 02:30.410
AUTOMATED VOICE:
Welcome to the American Museum
of Natural History.

02:30.410 --> 02:32.549
LIBBY: Vantablack was
a lab-created material

02:32.549 --> 02:35.020
that was said to be
the darkest black in existence.

02:35.020 --> 02:36.857
This way, please.
It was created for the military

02:36.857 --> 02:39.863
to help hide satellites
and jets from detection,

02:39.863 --> 02:41.265
and it is so dark

02:41.265 --> 02:43.403
that you're not even allowed
to use it, legally.

02:43.403 --> 02:45.107
What was --
that was crazy.

02:45.107 --> 02:47.310
MAN:
I did not expect that.

02:48.581 --> 02:50.117
It is the closest you can get

02:50.117 --> 02:53.457
to a physical manifestation
of the void.

02:53.457 --> 02:55.728
[ ominous music plays ]

02:55.728 --> 03:00.805
♪♪♪♪

03:02.140 --> 03:05.447
♪♪ Ah, ah ♪♪

03:06.884 --> 03:10.057
♪♪ Ah-ah-ah ♪♪

03:10.057 --> 03:12.428
How was it still July?

03:12.428 --> 03:14.232
♪♪ Ah ♪♪

03:14.232 --> 03:15.968
How many more days
until the fall?

03:15.968 --> 03:19.743
How many more days
until his kids returned?

03:19.743 --> 03:23.082
You can see the --
Finally, it was the work week.

03:23.082 --> 03:27.457
And finally, finally, he was
too busy to feel anything.

03:29.328 --> 03:31.098
But when the day came
to an end,

03:31.098 --> 03:32.635
as it always eventually did,

03:32.635 --> 03:36.175
he was left to face
another endless night.

03:36.175 --> 03:38.113
[ indistinct conversation ]

03:38.113 --> 03:39.381
Ooh!
Well, I just think --

03:39.381 --> 03:40.985
Guys. Hey.

03:40.985 --> 03:42.387
Oh, hey.

03:42.387 --> 03:43.691
- Hi.
JOANIE: Hi.

03:43.691 --> 03:45.126
You know, you guys have been
doing, uh,

03:45.126 --> 03:46.597
such a great job lately,
I was thinking I'd like to

03:46.597 --> 03:48.433
engage in --
in an age-old tradition

03:48.433 --> 03:50.003
and take you out
for a drink tonight.

03:50.003 --> 03:51.506
I have a date.
Um...

03:51.506 --> 03:53.544
And I have to --
I'm studying for boards.

03:53.544 --> 03:55.380
And I'm in Clay's
study group.

03:55.380 --> 03:57.117
No, that's cool.
So, I'll be, uh --

03:57.117 --> 03:58.420
Yeah, maybe, like,
another time or whatever.

03:58.420 --> 04:00.825
Doesn't matter.
Yeah.

04:00.825 --> 04:03.129
- Yeah.
WOMAN: Code pink -- third floor.

04:03.129 --> 04:05.467
Code pink -- third floor.

04:05.467 --> 04:08.473
LIBBY: Toby's loneliness
was now a monster.

04:08.473 --> 04:10.511
[ cellphone button beeps ]

04:10.511 --> 04:12.749
The story is,
they get to the glacier...

04:12.749 --> 04:14.284
[ cellphone ringing ]
...and the karate master,

04:14.284 --> 04:15.788
who's like a Yoda figure,

04:15.788 --> 04:18.226
but is also somehow
the tango champion of Spain --

04:18.226 --> 04:20.230
Hang on.
My man!

04:20.230 --> 04:22.334
Hey. Yeah, no,
I was just wondering

04:22.334 --> 04:24.171
what you're doing tonight.

04:24.171 --> 04:25.941
Well, my boy Brian
just got dumped,

04:25.941 --> 04:27.779
so we're taking him out
for a drink.

04:27.779 --> 04:29.983
Oh, okay.
That's too bad.

04:29.983 --> 04:31.720
Yeah, you should come.

04:31.720 --> 04:33.958
I don't think
I know Brian.

04:33.958 --> 04:36.029
Of course you do.

04:36.029 --> 04:38.132
Do you have a pen?
Take this down.

04:38.132 --> 04:41.941
[ crowd chanting "Toby!" ]

04:41.941 --> 04:43.409
[ laughter ]

04:43.409 --> 04:44.779
A little closer.

04:44.779 --> 04:47.786
[ indistinct conversations ]

04:47.786 --> 04:49.154
Keep your left arm
straight.

04:49.154 --> 04:50.324
Giddy-up!

04:50.324 --> 04:52.995
[ cheers and laughter ]

04:52.995 --> 04:54.331
That was exhilarating.

04:54.331 --> 04:56.035
I can't believe they have
a whole gym just for golf.

04:56.035 --> 04:57.471
And it's huge.

04:57.471 --> 04:58.608
We probably could have
just played, you know,

04:58.608 --> 04:59.676
like, real golf.
It's time?

04:59.676 --> 05:01.145
Ah!
Come on.

05:01.145 --> 05:02.448
What?
What are we doing?

05:02.448 --> 05:04.418
Annual Britney/Justin dance-off
re-enactment.

05:04.418 --> 05:05.721
Wait. What?
Come on.

05:05.721 --> 05:07.725
[ Nelly's "Hot in Herre" plays ]

05:07.725 --> 05:10.363
MAN:
Come on, Britney!

05:10.363 --> 05:12.902
WOMAN: Let's go, Britney!
MAN #2: Whoo!

05:15.040 --> 05:17.144
I don't really understand
how you, like, win a dance-off.

05:17.144 --> 05:19.816
Is it who dances better or,
like -- or, like, feistier?

05:19.816 --> 05:23.423
MAN #2: Whoo!
SETH: It doesn't matter, Toby.

05:23.423 --> 05:24.893
I always thought
the Justin/Britney dance-off

05:24.893 --> 05:26.596
was an urban legend.
Are you kidding?

05:26.596 --> 05:30.270
This was a defining moment
in American pop history.

05:30.270 --> 05:33.610
♪♪♪♪

05:33.610 --> 05:34.846
What time is it?

05:34.846 --> 05:36.048
Uh, 1:37.

05:36.048 --> 05:37.785
Shit!
We're late.

05:37.785 --> 05:39.589
Wait.
Late for what?

05:39.589 --> 05:42.495
[ punches landing,
crowd cheering ]

05:42.495 --> 05:44.766
[ grunting ]

05:44.766 --> 05:47.337
Come on!
Get up! Get up!

05:47.337 --> 05:48.874
Oh, shit!
Choke her!

05:48.874 --> 05:50.476
Is this totally kosher, like,
watching two women --

05:50.476 --> 05:51.680
- Toby!
- Yes.

05:51.680 --> 05:52.883
Do you not have
enough problems?

05:52.883 --> 05:54.351
No, no,
I have enough problems.

05:54.351 --> 05:55.889
Enjoy this.
It's one of the solutions.

05:55.889 --> 05:57.224
Okay.

05:57.224 --> 05:58.994
[ women grunting ]

05:58.994 --> 05:59.829
Yes!

05:59.829 --> 06:01.366
MAN:
Get up! Get up!

06:01.366 --> 06:03.771
Okay. Oh! We gotta go.
We gotta go.

06:03.771 --> 06:04.973
I don't know
if my guy won yet.

06:04.973 --> 06:06.610
What's happening?

06:06.610 --> 06:08.079
[ muffled conversations ]

06:08.079 --> 06:09.816
What is wrong with seeing
what you're eating?

06:09.816 --> 06:12.021
It's a sensory experience.
It's to feel the food,

06:12.021 --> 06:14.225
to really experience the moment,
you know?

06:14.225 --> 06:15.995
Well, you know,
I have a shellfish allergy.

06:15.995 --> 06:18.065
Do they know that?
I mean, who do I tell?

06:18.065 --> 06:19.201
You're thinking too hard.

06:19.201 --> 06:20.705
You've never experienced
anything like this.

06:20.705 --> 06:22.408
Yeah, you've never
experienced anaphylaxis.

06:22.408 --> 06:24.311
Try to enjoy it.

06:24.311 --> 06:25.648
I am.
I am enjoying it.

06:25.648 --> 06:28.452
I'm enjoying it.

06:28.452 --> 06:29.523
Oh, no.
What?

06:29.523 --> 06:30.791
I-I gotta pee.

06:31.325 --> 06:33.564
I have not been up this late --
or this early --

06:33.564 --> 06:35.267
since medical school.

06:35.267 --> 06:36.670
Wait.
So, let me just get this.

06:36.670 --> 06:38.006
So, that -- When you say
that you're just, like,

06:38.006 --> 06:40.744
going out for a drink, like,
that's what happens?

06:40.744 --> 06:43.416
Sometimes.
Amazing.

06:43.416 --> 06:44.686
Oh, hey, one sec.

06:44.686 --> 06:46.856
What?
Hey, man.

06:46.856 --> 06:49.061
Can I grab two of those
off of you?

06:49.061 --> 06:50.798
Sure.
$10 cool?

06:55.306 --> 06:57.244
Thanks.
Thank you, sir.

06:57.244 --> 06:58.446
That is so cool.

06:58.446 --> 07:00.383
All right,
so what now?

07:00.383 --> 07:01.853
Now we go home.
Okay.

07:01.853 --> 07:03.657
You want to end this
before the joggers come out

07:03.657 --> 07:05.595
and you start questioning
how you're living your life.

07:05.595 --> 07:06.763
Okay.
All right.

07:06.763 --> 07:07.899
I'll see you later?

07:07.899 --> 07:09.702
Yeah. Good night.
Thank you.

07:16.449 --> 07:18.654
[ down-tempo music plays ]

07:18.654 --> 07:19.989
Oh, um, sorry.

07:19.989 --> 07:21.425
I can't actually eat this,
but thank you.

07:21.425 --> 07:23.163
Okay, you got it.

07:23.163 --> 07:27.071
♪♪♪♪

07:27.071 --> 07:30.811
♪♪♪♪

07:30.811 --> 07:32.381
LIBBY:
It was never clear to Toby

07:32.381 --> 07:35.153
how long you were supposed
to watch a sunrise for.

07:35.153 --> 07:38.560
And without thought,
the loneliness returned.

07:42.368 --> 07:44.104
The moment was gone.

07:45.875 --> 07:47.378
He couldn't even hold on to it,

07:47.378 --> 07:50.584
because you hold on to it
by sharing it.

07:50.584 --> 07:54.726
He still had so much love
and nowhere to put it.

07:58.600 --> 07:59.702
TOBY: U up?

07:59.702 --> 08:01.172
[ text message whooshes ]

08:01.172 --> 08:04.679
♪♪♪♪

08:07.652 --> 08:09.723
So, what were you doing out
so late?

08:09.723 --> 08:10.891
TOBY: Well, you know,
I have this, uh,

08:10.891 --> 08:13.029
friend, Seth,
and he, um...

08:14.833 --> 08:16.570
[ chuckles ]
You know, actually, my --

08:16.570 --> 08:19.642
my kids are away, and, um,

08:19.642 --> 08:22.915
I've been having, like,
a tough time just --

08:22.915 --> 08:24.819
just lately, actually.

08:27.090 --> 08:28.528
Turn over.

08:28.528 --> 08:30.263
Just do it.

08:34.171 --> 08:35.908
Okay.

08:38.480 --> 08:40.584
[ clears throat ]

08:45.126 --> 08:47.064
Okay, what is that?

08:47.064 --> 08:50.705
Now, tell me
what I'm spelling.

08:50.705 --> 08:53.009
[ laughs ]
Okay. Um...

08:53.009 --> 08:56.081
I think that --
I think that's a "T."

08:56.081 --> 08:57.652
Later, he wouldn't remember

08:57.652 --> 08:59.690
what she spelled out
on to his back.

08:59.690 --> 09:02.260
That's either an "A"
or an "H."

09:02.260 --> 09:04.331
He would only remember
thinking how strange it was

09:04.331 --> 09:07.304
for someone to be doing
something like this for him,

09:07.304 --> 09:08.774
something nice,

09:08.774 --> 09:11.847
where he was the only recipient
of the niceness.

09:11.847 --> 09:14.853
That's definitely
an "A."

09:14.853 --> 09:16.455
He couldn't remember one time

09:16.455 --> 09:18.494
where that had
ever happened to him.

09:18.494 --> 09:22.502
♪♪♪♪

09:22.502 --> 09:26.275
♪♪♪♪

09:26.275 --> 09:29.649
So, I guess we're not
going out to eat.

09:29.649 --> 09:30.751
I gotta be somewhere.

09:30.751 --> 09:32.487
Okay. I kind of just
want to know

09:32.487 --> 09:34.124
what I'm getting into
here.

09:34.124 --> 09:36.328
We're having fun,
aren't we?

09:36.328 --> 09:38.332
Yeah, we -- It's fun.

09:38.332 --> 09:40.102
You know, it's weird.

09:42.942 --> 09:44.912
Okay, listen.
Yeah?

09:48.152 --> 09:52.194
My husband is an anchor
on a conservative news network.

09:52.194 --> 09:53.898
You would know him.

09:53.898 --> 09:55.333
Is it Tucker Carlson?

09:55.333 --> 09:57.170
Uh, it doesn't matter.

09:57.170 --> 09:59.275
You can look it up.
I am not allowed to say.

09:59.275 --> 10:01.647
All right, fine, but were you
married to Tucker Carlson?

10:01.647 --> 10:03.282
Because --
Just listen.

10:03.282 --> 10:04.686
I was married,

10:04.686 --> 10:08.627
and we always had
this weird relationship.

10:08.627 --> 10:10.196
He was a very religious
Christian.

10:10.196 --> 10:13.135
I was Jewish.
My parents are conservative.

10:13.135 --> 10:16.342
Lower-case "C,"
but also upper-case, you know?

10:16.342 --> 10:17.511
Mm-hmm.

10:17.511 --> 10:19.414
And my parents,
when they came from Iran,

10:19.414 --> 10:21.986
they had all these ideas
of what a girl should be.

10:21.986 --> 10:24.058
She should be shy,
never let anyone touch her,

10:24.058 --> 10:25.995
never touch herself.
Sure, yeah.

10:25.995 --> 10:27.798
You know?
Yeah.

10:27.798 --> 10:30.638
And my husband
hated sex.

10:30.638 --> 10:32.207
I was a virgin
when I married him.

10:32.207 --> 10:35.113
I was such
a good little girl.

10:35.113 --> 10:38.921
And so I just thought there
was something wrong with me

10:38.921 --> 10:42.895
that I wanted
to have sex so much.

10:42.895 --> 10:46.970
Anyway, I came home
one day early

10:46.970 --> 10:49.910
from some dumb fundraiser,
and I walk in,

10:49.910 --> 10:53.684
and his assistant is
giving him a blow job.

10:53.684 --> 10:55.521
Wow.
His male assistant.

10:55.521 --> 10:57.224
Ah. I see.

10:57.224 --> 11:00.129
So, his job has
a morality clause,

11:00.129 --> 11:02.400
and being gay is immoral.

11:02.400 --> 11:03.604
Oh, yikes.

11:03.604 --> 11:04.972
This is them, not me,
obviously.

11:04.972 --> 11:06.408
Yeah, no, right.

11:06.408 --> 11:10.349
And so he pays for my life
and all of this,

11:10.349 --> 11:12.989
and I still, on occasion,
have to go with him

11:12.989 --> 11:15.961
to events
and awards shows.

11:15.961 --> 11:17.965
I'm not really divorced.

11:17.965 --> 11:19.569
Not technically.

11:19.569 --> 11:22.407
But we're -- we're done.

11:22.407 --> 11:24.478
Yeah, but, I mean,
is it worth it,

11:24.478 --> 11:27.450
not having your freedom,
not being able to start over?

11:28.921 --> 11:30.724
And you're so free?

11:30.724 --> 11:31.993
Yeah.
I'm divorced.

11:31.993 --> 11:33.229
I signed the papers.

11:33.229 --> 11:34.732
I have the freedom
to move on, yeah.

11:34.732 --> 11:37.103
[ scoffs ]

11:37.103 --> 11:39.942
Being divorced doesn't make you
any less married.

11:43.483 --> 11:45.019
[ sighs ]
I gotta go.

11:45.019 --> 11:47.190
Yeah. Oh.
Yeah, me too.

11:55.741 --> 11:58.112
[ indistinct
background chatter ]

12:05.560 --> 12:07.998
[ dog barking in distance ]

12:14.245 --> 12:16.650
What's up, man?
What's up?

12:16.650 --> 12:18.252
Aww.

12:21.960 --> 12:24.331
[ barks and whines ]

12:24.331 --> 12:28.707
♪♪♪♪

12:28.707 --> 12:30.476
Hello. Hi.

12:33.216 --> 12:35.521
Okay, that's good.
Now stay with me.

12:35.521 --> 12:37.023
Stay with me.

12:37.023 --> 12:38.594
This was what he needed --

12:38.594 --> 12:39.962
someone loyal,

12:39.962 --> 12:41.699
someone to bring
the family together

12:41.699 --> 12:43.870
and replace what they had lost.

12:45.507 --> 12:47.343
What he'd lost.

12:50.249 --> 12:51.820
It's like I have this book,
right?

12:51.820 --> 12:56.295
And it's, like, right beyond
my fingers, in my head, but...

12:56.295 --> 12:58.901
I never actually do anything
about it.

12:58.901 --> 13:00.804
Well, what's it about?

13:02.440 --> 13:04.477
Maybe it'll be
about smoking.

13:04.477 --> 13:06.381
I'd read that.
[ scoffs ] Yeah.

13:07.618 --> 13:10.957
You know, I read once
that people who have affairs --

13:10.957 --> 13:13.029
they're not really trying
to betray their partners

13:13.029 --> 13:15.032
and they're not really in love
with someone else,

13:15.032 --> 13:17.170
but they're trying to find
who they are again.

13:17.170 --> 13:18.439
They're trying to go back
to the moment

13:18.439 --> 13:20.544
when they were
last themselves.

13:20.544 --> 13:23.583
That's what I think
about your smoking.

13:23.583 --> 13:25.119
Hmm.

13:25.119 --> 13:27.992
That's actually a very
insightful thing to say.

13:27.992 --> 13:29.461
I'm a very
insightful guy.

13:29.461 --> 13:31.799
I guess so.

13:31.799 --> 13:33.002
Hello.

13:33.002 --> 13:34.304
What is this?
What did you do?

13:34.304 --> 13:37.043
This is Bubbles,
Bubbles Fleishman.

13:37.043 --> 13:38.412
Bubbles, say hello.

13:38.412 --> 13:40.349
You felt like you finally had
an empty house

13:40.349 --> 13:42.821
and a few weeks of freedom,
and it was just too much.

13:42.821 --> 13:44.157
It was.
It was overwhelming.

13:44.157 --> 13:45.594
Yes, say hi to Seth.
Hi.

13:45.594 --> 13:47.297
And say hi to Libby,
who we love, too.

13:47.297 --> 13:48.433
Mm-hmm.

13:48.433 --> 13:50.236
You're a very nice
person.

13:50.236 --> 13:52.708
Yes, you know, the kids have
wanted a dog for a long time.

13:52.708 --> 13:54.879
Hannah always said she wanted
a dachshund named Bubbles

13:54.879 --> 13:56.282
since she was like 3.

13:56.282 --> 13:57.484
And I think I can have
the dog house-trained

13:57.484 --> 13:58.887
by the time
they get back home.

13:58.887 --> 14:00.624
Such a divorced-dad thing.

14:00.624 --> 14:02.194
I am such a divorced dad.

14:02.194 --> 14:05.100
You realize that that's
a lifelong commitment, right?

14:05.100 --> 14:08.840
Like, you have to take care
of that or it dies.

14:08.840 --> 14:11.278
Yeah, I know.
I know. I hear you.

14:11.278 --> 14:13.517
I'm sorry I was, like,
shitty to you, okay?

14:13.517 --> 14:15.019
What is going on?

14:15.019 --> 14:17.424
Can I just say, you will never
believe what we did last night.

14:17.424 --> 14:20.196
Oh, last -- Another night that
I didn't get invited to.

14:20.196 --> 14:21.533
Awesome!
It was incredible.

14:21.533 --> 14:23.368
Like, we owned the city.
We went everywhere.

14:23.368 --> 14:25.106
I think we ate
an endangered species.

14:25.106 --> 14:26.576
- Ew.
- No, no, no, it was amazing.

14:26.576 --> 14:28.547
It was like -- like the world
existed just for us.

14:28.547 --> 14:30.684
It's weird.
I never, like -- I never, like,

14:30.684 --> 14:32.955
understood that life,
but now I think

14:32.955 --> 14:34.725
I want every night
of my life to do that.

14:34.725 --> 14:36.361
It was glorious.

14:36.361 --> 14:38.099
Yeah. What?
Right, Seth?

14:38.099 --> 14:40.069
- I don't know.
- What -- what do you mean?

14:40.069 --> 14:41.305
We had a time.
Did we not have a time?

14:41.305 --> 14:42.641
Yeah, no, no, no.
We did, we did.

14:42.641 --> 14:44.778
I don't know.
I'm just kind of depressed.

14:44.778 --> 14:45.915
Y-You?

14:45.915 --> 14:47.484
Really?
You're depressed?

14:47.484 --> 14:48.754
I can't be depressed?

14:48.754 --> 14:50.356
Yeah, I don't know.
You have this, like, great life.

14:50.356 --> 14:52.461
Okay.
What happened?

14:52.461 --> 14:54.932
What happened is,
I got fired.

14:54.932 --> 14:56.569
What happened is that
I wear a suit all day

14:56.569 --> 14:58.205
because I might get
a job interview

14:58.205 --> 15:01.478
and I'm 41
and I have no one to cry to.

15:01.478 --> 15:03.282
I don't know,
I turned around and realized

15:03.282 --> 15:05.153
that the brokers who are
15 years younger than me

15:05.153 --> 15:06.923
are the only friends I had.

15:06.923 --> 15:08.326
- What about us?
- Yeah.

15:08.326 --> 15:09.862
Yeah, I know. Like I said,
can't I just be depressed?

15:09.862 --> 15:11.566
Wait. But we, like --
We had the night of our lives.

15:11.566 --> 15:12.869
Did we not?
I don't know, dude.

15:12.869 --> 15:13.938
That was like a Monday
for me.

15:13.938 --> 15:16.676
Oh, my God.

15:16.676 --> 15:18.145
What the hell is that?

15:18.145 --> 15:20.483
It's just incense, Dad.
Don't worry about it.

15:21.351 --> 15:23.189
My job was supposed
to be failsafe.

15:23.189 --> 15:24.959
Nothing --
Nothing is failsafe.

15:24.959 --> 15:27.163
Yeah, but I didn't
do anything.

15:27.163 --> 15:29.502
If you didn't do anything,
then you should sue.

15:31.272 --> 15:32.675
I don't want
to talk about it.

15:32.675 --> 15:33.910
Did you tell Vanessa yet?

15:33.910 --> 15:35.346
How can I tell Vanessa?
It's too late.

15:35.346 --> 15:36.816
- Oh.
- I have to break up with her.

15:36.816 --> 15:38.086
Are you crazy?

15:38.086 --> 15:40.724
Well, I would have to admit
I lied.

15:40.724 --> 15:42.528
I would have to apologize.

15:42.528 --> 15:44.665
Love means never having
to say you're sorry.

15:44.665 --> 15:46.368
Actually, in my experience,
it's divorce

15:46.368 --> 15:47.871
that means never having
to say you're sorry, yeah.

15:47.871 --> 15:49.207
- Oh.
- Yes, he's right.

15:49.207 --> 15:50.577
Every relationship
I've ever had

15:50.577 --> 15:53.382
is a girl asking me
to apologize all the time.

15:53.382 --> 15:55.587
Mm, kind of a strange way
of maybe looking

15:55.587 --> 15:58.593
at your ongoing issues
with women, but sure.

15:58.593 --> 16:01.131
I don't want to talk about it,
like I said.

16:03.201 --> 16:05.206
Oh, shit.
I have to go.

16:05.206 --> 16:07.077
My flight leaves
in like four hours.

16:07.077 --> 16:08.680
Oh, you are gonna have
a great time.

16:08.680 --> 16:09.982
Where you going?

16:09.982 --> 16:11.853
- [Bleep]
- Oh, I love it there.

16:11.853 --> 16:13.757
Mm-hmm.
Bye, guys.

16:13.757 --> 16:16.061
The multinational mass media
and entertainment

16:16.061 --> 16:18.465
conglomerate that features
several amusement parks

16:18.465 --> 16:20.169
as its profit center
would rather

16:20.169 --> 16:21.573
I didn't mention it by name.

16:21.573 --> 16:23.509
ADAM:
Come on, in the car.

16:26.481 --> 16:28.853
Thank you.
I'm sorry.

16:28.920 --> 16:30.256
Thank you.
I'm sorry.

16:30.256 --> 16:31.592
I've just got to get
a few things, okay?

16:31.592 --> 16:33.429
- I did it. You're late.
- I know. I just --

16:33.429 --> 16:34.799
- Let's go!
- I'm gonna run upstairs.

16:34.799 --> 16:36.202
I'm gonna do deodorant.
I'll be right back.

16:36.202 --> 16:37.337
I had this timed
to the minute, Lib.

16:37.337 --> 16:38.640
LIBBY:
I'll be right back!

16:39.709 --> 16:42.548
I'm sorry, I'm sorry,
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

16:42.548 --> 16:43.683
That's okay.

16:43.683 --> 16:46.889
At least you got
the restaurant reservations.

16:46.889 --> 16:48.727
Right.

16:48.727 --> 16:51.264
[ engine starts ]

16:51.264 --> 16:53.168
DRIVER:
Newark Airport, right?

16:55.039 --> 16:57.712
The multinational mass media
and entertainment

16:57.712 --> 17:00.282
conglomerate that features
several amusement parks

17:00.282 --> 17:01.953
as its profit center
would rather

17:01.953 --> 17:04.859
I not depict scenes
from this vacation.

17:04.859 --> 17:07.865
So instead of telling you
about my trip to there,

17:07.865 --> 17:12.575
I will use this time to tell
you about my trip to here,

17:12.575 --> 17:16.583
meaning how I got here
to this place in my life.

17:16.583 --> 17:18.285
I worked at a men's magazine,

17:18.285 --> 17:20.356
the only place
I ever wanted to work.

17:20.356 --> 17:21.593
It's really ingenious.

17:21.593 --> 17:23.195
MAN: Masterful.
MAN #2: Killed it.

17:23.195 --> 17:24.866
I loved it there.

17:24.866 --> 17:28.472
I was an editorial assistant,
then a news assistant.

17:28.472 --> 17:30.778
Hey, you're taking notes,
right?

17:30.778 --> 17:32.781
Yeah.

17:32.781 --> 17:36.889
All I wanted was to be a writer
with my stories up there.

17:36.889 --> 17:38.827
To write those stories
seemed to me

17:38.827 --> 17:43.202
to be the closest approximation
of actually living.

17:43.202 --> 17:44.706
Or, more specifically,
what I wanted

17:44.706 --> 17:47.377
was to be Archer Sylvan,
our most marquee writer,

17:47.377 --> 17:49.682
who wrote bombastic,
wild stories

17:49.682 --> 17:51.485
that stopped the world
for a week

17:51.485 --> 17:53.089
after they were published.

17:53.089 --> 17:54.592
Archer spanned the globe

17:54.592 --> 17:56.663
digging up
unbelievable characters

17:56.663 --> 17:59.034
and telling a story that felt
like you were being gripped

17:59.034 --> 18:01.572
by the lapels and shouted at.

18:01.572 --> 18:03.577
Of course,
The Heart is a Lonely Dinner

18:03.577 --> 18:05.780
was his most famous story.

18:05.780 --> 18:07.751
It won
the National Magazine Award

18:07.751 --> 18:11.257
the year it was published
and was a Pulitzer finalist.

18:14.464 --> 18:16.636
My favorite of his books,
Decoupling,

18:16.636 --> 18:19.708
was a National Book Award-
winning scandal,

18:19.708 --> 18:21.980
a gonzo account of a year
in the life

18:21.980 --> 18:23.750
of a divorced man in 1979.

18:23.750 --> 18:25.385
You like that one, huh?
Okay, good.

18:25.385 --> 18:27.290
As the years went on,
though, Archer,

18:27.290 --> 18:29.394
who had once been
everyone's delight,

18:29.394 --> 18:32.133
became the subject
of evermore controversy.

18:32.133 --> 18:33.603
Well, what would you say
to people

18:33.603 --> 18:36.843
who thought that only showing
one side of the divorce

18:36.843 --> 18:38.445
gave women short shrift?

18:38.445 --> 18:40.049
[ chuckles ]
I mean, come on, Jake.

18:40.049 --> 18:43.222
Have you ever asked a woman
what her divorce was like?

18:43.222 --> 18:45.260
How do you mean?
[ mimics snoring ]

18:45.260 --> 18:46.763
[ laughter ]

18:46.763 --> 18:48.065
I don't get the joke.

18:48.065 --> 18:50.737
All right, well, I'm saying
it's the same old thing,

18:50.737 --> 18:51.939
the same story.

18:51.939 --> 18:54.111
Uh, "He did me wrong.
He cheated on me.

18:54.111 --> 18:56.148
He doesn't respect me."

18:56.148 --> 18:57.618
I'm tired of that story.

18:57.618 --> 19:00.390
I wanted to write the story
of a person's soul.

19:00.390 --> 19:03.029
So a woman
doesn't have a soul?

19:03.029 --> 19:04.599
I didn't say that.

19:04.599 --> 19:07.436
I'm saying that you can't get
to the truth of a thing

19:07.436 --> 19:08.706
if you ask her.

19:08.706 --> 19:10.275
So women don't
tell the truth?

19:10.275 --> 19:12.213
Now, see, this is
what critics take issue with

19:12.213 --> 19:13.482
about you, Archer.

19:13.482 --> 19:15.153
You wrote about
a man's divorce,

19:15.153 --> 19:16.589
taking his word
for everything,

19:16.589 --> 19:20.162
never interviewed the woman
to verify anything.

19:20.162 --> 19:22.233
It's not the same thing.

19:22.233 --> 19:23.737
Well, they're reissuing
the book, Jake.

19:23.737 --> 19:25.674
That's got to count
for something.

19:25.674 --> 19:27.845
[ laughter ]

19:27.845 --> 19:31.485
Some of the lines that were
now considered unspeakable

19:31.485 --> 19:33.590
were edited out
of later editions,

19:33.590 --> 19:36.830
but they didn't fix
its iconic last line.

19:36.830 --> 19:40.537
"The bitch will try to get you
every time."

19:40.537 --> 19:42.173
But I didn't care.

19:42.173 --> 19:45.480
I forgave anything that was
as exciting and angry

19:45.480 --> 19:47.216
and urgent as this.

19:47.216 --> 19:49.253
[ laughs ]
Hey, Archer.

19:49.253 --> 19:50.891
Hey.
I work, uh --

19:50.891 --> 19:52.627
I work at the magazine.

19:52.627 --> 19:54.598
I've never seen you there.

19:54.598 --> 19:57.470
Oh, well, I'm --
I'm such a huge fan of yours.

19:57.470 --> 19:59.073
I had to just come
and hear you --

19:59.073 --> 20:00.577
see you --
see you speak.

20:00.577 --> 20:02.714
Right.
That piece that you wrote

20:02.714 --> 20:06.488
about the Fountain of Youth
in the Andes -- that story --

20:06.488 --> 20:09.628
it completely changed my life
when I read it.

20:09.628 --> 20:12.133
It was, um --
What's your name?

20:12.133 --> 20:13.537
Libby Slater.

20:13.537 --> 20:15.707
[ pen scribbling ]

20:15.707 --> 20:17.276
Here you go.
Thank you.

20:17.276 --> 20:18.980
- Hey.
- Hi.

20:19.515 --> 20:21.919
WOMAN: Good night, sweetie.
Sorry. Good night.

20:21.919 --> 20:22.988
MAN: This way.

20:22.988 --> 20:24.290
[ clears throat ]

20:24.290 --> 20:26.227
Hi.

20:28.165 --> 20:29.769
Almost 15 years later,

20:29.769 --> 20:33.977
I was still jogging in place
at the magazine.

20:33.977 --> 20:38.753
And the magazine
was still celebrating Archer.

20:38.753 --> 20:40.657
It was always the next story
for me

20:40.657 --> 20:42.928
that was going to be
the big one.

20:42.928 --> 20:44.698
I was always just about
to break out.

20:44.698 --> 20:47.070
My fingers attracted
the blood --

20:47.070 --> 20:50.376
you know, attracted
the tiger sharks.

20:50.376 --> 20:51.913
And I kept telling them,

20:51.913 --> 20:53.984
"I didn't mean to run
with the bulls.

20:53.984 --> 20:56.655
I was doing a story on these
bank robbers

20:56.655 --> 20:59.562
when they started
getting chased by the cops."

20:59.562 --> 21:01.197
That's when I saw
the most beautiful woman

21:01.197 --> 21:02.567
I'd ever seen before.

21:02.567 --> 21:03.903
Don't ask me
how old she was.

21:03.903 --> 21:06.275
She lived outside
the realm of time.

21:06.275 --> 21:08.112
[ laughter ]

21:08.112 --> 21:10.917
[ crowd chanting "Read it!" ]

21:10.917 --> 21:12.019
All right, all right!

21:12.019 --> 21:15.259
If you insist!
I'm gonna read one page.

21:15.259 --> 21:17.029
[ indistinct conversations ]

21:17.029 --> 21:18.499
We should be thinking that
for you,

21:18.499 --> 21:19.802
because she's a child star,

21:19.802 --> 21:22.373
but she's not really
a girl, right?

21:22.373 --> 21:23.743
I don't know, Glenn.

21:23.743 --> 21:25.514
I mean, why can't I do
something more like

21:25.514 --> 21:27.985
what Archer does?

21:27.985 --> 21:29.888
Archer is Archer.
You know that.

21:29.888 --> 21:31.625
- I know.
- Everyone wants to be Archer.

21:31.625 --> 21:33.162
He's the house style.

21:33.162 --> 21:34.765
Let's get you
something good.

21:34.765 --> 21:36.636
Um, uh...

21:36.636 --> 21:40.142
NFL cheerleader coaches.

21:40.142 --> 21:42.581
NFL cheerleader coaches?

21:42.581 --> 21:43.917
- Tony Bennett?
- Tony Bennett?

21:43.917 --> 21:46.121
He's turning 85.
It might be surprising.

21:46.121 --> 21:47.423
Surpri-- Like what?

21:47.423 --> 21:49.460
He-might-die-during-the-
interview surprising?

21:49.460 --> 21:50.764
It's the legend.

21:50.764 --> 21:52.835
Lib, you killed
that Instagram story.

21:52.835 --> 21:54.204
- Thank you.
- Killed it, murdered it.

21:54.204 --> 21:55.707
Destroyed.
I'm in awe.

21:55.707 --> 21:59.080
Steiner was just sent to Cuba
on a Castro story.

21:59.080 --> 22:01.752
You're kidding.

22:01.752 --> 22:03.322
- Steiner!
- Hey, buddy.

22:03.322 --> 22:05.359
That guy has been here
for six months!

22:05.359 --> 22:06.461
He came over from GQ.

22:06.461 --> 22:07.665
He was there
for two years.

22:07.665 --> 22:09.434
He's got a voice.

22:09.434 --> 22:11.906
I have a voice.

22:11.906 --> 22:13.543
You know what I mean,
Libby.

22:13.543 --> 22:17.918
So, you have a dinosaur
whose work has aged like milk,

22:17.918 --> 22:18.920
and you're what?

22:18.920 --> 22:21.457
Like, grooming
a baby dinosaur?

22:22.962 --> 22:25.066
Let's get you
on a new story.

22:25.066 --> 22:30.176
♪♪♪♪

22:30.176 --> 22:35.286
♪♪♪♪

22:35.286 --> 22:40.162
♪♪♪♪

22:40.162 --> 22:42.634
I had first read Decoupling
in college.

22:42.634 --> 22:44.805
In fact, I had given it to Toby
in Israel,

22:44.805 --> 22:48.680
and he'd become an
Archer Sylvan obsessive, too.

22:48.680 --> 22:52.654
That night, I reread
Archer's collection.

22:52.654 --> 22:56.094
I'd been at the magazine
for 15 years by then.

22:58.800 --> 23:01.806
It had taken me
to right exactly that party

23:01.806 --> 23:04.912
to realize that I was
no longer moving forward.

23:04.912 --> 23:07.016
I was completely stalled.

23:07.016 --> 23:11.525
♪♪♪♪

23:12.994 --> 23:14.731
What's going on?

23:17.403 --> 23:19.040
I don't know.

23:21.946 --> 23:25.152
I'm lost.
I don't know what I'm doing.

23:25.152 --> 23:27.290
Why?
What happened?

23:28.392 --> 23:34.036
I just was rereading
The Heart is a Lonely Dinner.

23:34.036 --> 23:35.406
[ sighs ]

23:35.406 --> 23:36.742
I just -- I don't know.

23:36.742 --> 23:39.047
I always thought,
like, I --

23:39.047 --> 23:41.986
If I write good stories,
if I proved myself...

23:43.956 --> 23:45.727
...then one day,
they're gonna send me

23:45.727 --> 23:46.962
to the top of the mountain

23:46.962 --> 23:49.835
to eat the still-beating
heart of the ox.

23:49.835 --> 23:52.039
And I'll know
the secret to life.

23:52.039 --> 23:53.576
You'll get there.
You will.

23:53.576 --> 23:55.212
I won't, I won't, I won't.
I won't. I won't.

23:55.212 --> 23:56.882
I'm not even close.

23:59.253 --> 24:03.161
Oh, God, I can't believe
I'm saying this, but...

24:05.567 --> 24:08.338
...I think
I have to leave.

24:08.338 --> 24:09.641
Listen.
Come here.

24:09.641 --> 24:10.643
Come here.

24:10.643 --> 24:14.217
[ sighs ]
Listen.

24:14.217 --> 24:17.156
Those guys who embody
the ethic of the magazine --

24:17.156 --> 24:19.327
they're blowhards.

24:19.327 --> 24:21.499
They come to you
when they want a good story

24:21.499 --> 24:23.569
without the pages
soaked in blood.

24:23.569 --> 24:26.509
They come to me
when they want a story

24:26.509 --> 24:29.948
that's filed on time.

24:29.948 --> 24:33.890
They do. I want to soak
my pages in blood.

24:33.890 --> 24:36.094
You know, I want people
to read my stories

24:36.094 --> 24:38.667
and cry
and rend their garments.

24:38.667 --> 24:39.935
- They will.
- They don't!

24:39.935 --> 24:42.741
They don't.
They don't!

24:44.377 --> 24:45.847
God.

24:45.847 --> 24:48.586
I just feel so stupid.

24:48.586 --> 24:51.024
I was never in the game.

24:51.024 --> 24:53.830
You could be a great writer
at a men's magazine,

24:53.830 --> 24:55.600
but no matter
how hard you work,

24:55.600 --> 24:57.103
if you're a woman,
you can't be a man.

24:57.103 --> 24:59.508
It's like I don't even feel
like anybody reads anything

24:59.508 --> 25:01.812
I write
unless it's about a man.

25:08.660 --> 25:10.229
I'll write a novel.

25:10.229 --> 25:12.333
[ down-tempo music plays ]

25:12.333 --> 25:15.707
♪♪♪♪

25:15.707 --> 25:17.811
But now it's two years later.

25:20.349 --> 25:23.255
I haven't once even opened
a blank page

25:23.255 --> 25:25.092
and made an attempt.

25:25.092 --> 25:27.497
And here's the secret
of my vacation --

25:27.497 --> 25:30.202
that while we were on the rides
and standing in lines

25:30.202 --> 25:33.909
and taking pictures,
I wasn't really with my family.

25:36.415 --> 25:38.118
I wasn't in Florida.

25:40.356 --> 25:42.092
I wasn't on an airplane.

25:42.092 --> 25:44.364
I wasn't at a themed
restaurant, begging a hostess

25:44.364 --> 25:46.234
for a reservation
everyone in the world

25:46.234 --> 25:48.939
knew to make weeks before,
but not me.

25:53.449 --> 25:56.254
I wasn't even at home,
unloading the car.

25:58.626 --> 26:01.031
I don't know what to do
with you.

26:01.031 --> 26:06.509
♪♪♪♪

26:06.509 --> 26:12.186
♪♪♪♪

26:12.186 --> 26:13.388
I was with Toby.

26:13.388 --> 26:16.093
[ cellphone ringing ]

26:21.438 --> 26:23.475
[ dog whines ]

26:23.475 --> 26:25.212
Oh, shit!

26:25.212 --> 26:26.715
Come here.

26:26.715 --> 26:28.051
Okay.
Here we go.

26:28.051 --> 26:29.721
Okay.

26:29.721 --> 26:30.857
[ ringing continues ]

26:30.857 --> 26:32.660
Okay, come on.

26:34.732 --> 26:36.168
Okay.
It's okay.

26:36.168 --> 26:39.541
Go pee. Go pee.
Go pee. Go pee.

26:39.541 --> 26:41.546
Okay, there you go.
Go pee.

26:41.546 --> 26:42.848
Come on.
Okay.

26:42.848 --> 26:44.450
- She's so cute.
- Oh, hey.

26:44.450 --> 26:45.452
Thank you so much, yeah.

26:45.452 --> 26:46.722
What's her name?

26:46.722 --> 26:48.125
Oh, it's actually, uh --
it's actually a boy.

26:48.125 --> 26:49.728
People do think it's a girl,
but it's actually a boy.

26:49.728 --> 26:51.330
- Oh.
- Uh, Bubbles.

26:51.330 --> 26:52.968
Maybe that's why they think
it's a girl.

26:52.968 --> 26:54.805
[ cellphone ringing ]
Yeah, maybe.

26:54.805 --> 26:56.876
Shit.
Sorry.

26:56.876 --> 26:58.646
Shit.
It's my kids' camp.

26:58.646 --> 26:59.915
Hello.
Dr. Fleishman.

26:59.915 --> 27:02.153
Are the --
Yeah, are the kids okay?

27:02.153 --> 27:04.825
Wait. No. Sorry.
You have to tell me.

27:04.825 --> 27:06.427
Now? I'm sorry.
I have a job.

27:06.427 --> 27:08.866
But can you please just at least
tell me, like, the nature --

27:08.866 --> 27:10.836
Yeah, I don't even have a car.
How am I supposed to --

27:10.836 --> 27:12.641
Yeah, fine.
That's fine.

27:12.641 --> 27:14.778
I'll -- I'll be in
as soon as possible.

27:14.778 --> 27:15.947
Yeah, thanks.

27:15.947 --> 27:17.518
You need to clean up
that dog shit.

27:17.518 --> 27:19.186
What?

27:22.494 --> 27:24.330
Shit. Uh...

27:28.939 --> 27:30.743
[ dog barking ]

27:34.618 --> 27:35.820
TOBY: Hi.
- Hey.

27:35.820 --> 27:36.956
Thank you for coming,
truly.

27:36.956 --> 27:38.526
I was taking
the day off anyway.

27:38.526 --> 27:39.928
Oh, yeah?
Everything okay?

27:39.928 --> 27:41.330
I don't know.
That douchebag camp director

27:41.330 --> 27:43.435
wouldn't tell me anything.
It's Bubbles!

27:43.435 --> 27:44.938
I'm sure everything's fine.

27:44.938 --> 27:46.207
How could it be fine?
How could anything be fine?

27:46.207 --> 27:47.511
Do you remember
the times a parent

27:47.511 --> 27:48.546
had to pick up a kid
from camp?

27:48.546 --> 27:49.849
Michael Goldstein?

27:49.849 --> 27:51.852
When he urinated
on Scott Messinger.

27:51.852 --> 27:52.988
Yeah, exactly.

27:52.988 --> 27:55.358
Don't worry.
Children are resilient.

27:57.664 --> 27:59.267
He wondered why
people say that.

27:59.267 --> 28:01.738
Children are actually
not resilient.

28:01.738 --> 28:03.174
They're children.

28:03.174 --> 28:04.745
Just because they don't
jump off a bridge

28:04.745 --> 28:06.848
doesn't mean they're resilient.

28:09.253 --> 28:11.558
RACHEL PLATTEN:
♪♪ This is my fight song ♪♪

28:11.558 --> 28:15.232
♪♪ Take-back-my-life song,
prove I'm alr-- ♪♪

28:15.232 --> 28:18.138
[ Calum Scott and Tiesto's
"Dancing on My Own" plays ]

28:18.138 --> 28:20.342
♪♪ And I'm giving it my all ♪♪

28:20.342 --> 28:25.118
♪♪ But I'm not the guy
you're taking home ♪♪

28:25.118 --> 28:27.156
♪♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪♪

28:27.156 --> 28:30.129
♪♪ I keep dancing on my own ♪♪

28:30.129 --> 28:31.364
CAMP DIRECTOR: Mr. Fleishman.
TOBY: Mm-hmm.

28:31.364 --> 28:34.470
Everything's fine.
Hannah's fine.

28:34.470 --> 28:37.009
But she did take, uh,

28:37.009 --> 28:39.781
an unfortunate picture
with her phone,

28:39.781 --> 28:42.653
and she shared it
with a young man.

28:42.653 --> 28:44.858
What?
What kind of picture?

28:44.858 --> 28:46.962
Well, it was a very
suggestive picture.

28:46.962 --> 28:51.572
Um, the boy shared it
with his friends.

28:51.572 --> 28:53.308
He shared it
with his friends.

28:55.112 --> 28:57.416
And what does
"suggestive" mean?

28:57.416 --> 29:00.756
Well, it was, uh --
It wasn't appropriate.

29:00.756 --> 29:03.529
Um, I'll let you discuss it
with Hannah.

29:03.529 --> 29:04.931
But suffice it to say,

29:04.931 --> 29:07.103
it violated our
camper code of conduct.

29:07.103 --> 29:09.675
Yeah, I'm not really interested
in the camper code of conduct.

29:09.675 --> 29:10.843
Is she okay?

29:10.843 --> 29:11.913
Oh, yeah. Yeah.

29:11.913 --> 29:13.148
I-I said that.
She's fine.

29:13.148 --> 29:14.651
Where is she?
I want to see my daughter.

29:14.651 --> 29:16.688
- She's packing up her things.
- Right. And, um --

29:16.688 --> 29:18.091
And what's happening
to him?

29:18.091 --> 29:19.628
- To?
- To the kid.

29:19.628 --> 29:21.665
- Well, Mr. Fleishman --
- Actually, it's Dr. Fleishman.

29:21.665 --> 29:26.207
Okay. Well, he's not the one
that took the photo, so --

29:26.207 --> 29:27.744
Right.
So nothing's happening to him.

29:27.744 --> 29:29.948
He didn't violate any of your
policies or any of your rules?

29:29.948 --> 29:32.119
- Well, right now, um...
- Yeah.

29:32.119 --> 29:33.555
...h-his parents are
in Switzerland,

29:33.555 --> 29:34.691
so we talked to him.

29:34.691 --> 29:35.960
How nice.
How nice for them.

29:35.960 --> 29:37.897
Okay, where is she?

29:37.897 --> 29:40.168
[ Hannah sniffling ]

29:47.115 --> 29:49.253
- Hannahbear.
- [ sobs ]

29:49.253 --> 29:52.961
Come here.
Come here, come here.

29:52.961 --> 29:54.497
Oh, honey.

29:55.733 --> 29:58.840
I know there's so little
I can say to make this better,

29:58.840 --> 30:00.676
but...here.

30:00.676 --> 30:02.079
Listen to me.
Listen to me.

30:02.079 --> 30:05.085
Honey, it won't always
feel this bad, okay?

30:05.085 --> 30:06.955
[ crying ]
I just want to go.

30:06.955 --> 30:08.058
Yeah, no, I understand,
I understand.

30:08.058 --> 30:09.160
We'll go, we'll go.

30:09.160 --> 30:10.897
Hey, where --
where is Solly?

30:10.897 --> 30:13.334
He's in Chipmunks.
[ sobs ]

30:14.571 --> 30:15.940
I was having
a great time.

30:15.940 --> 30:17.677
I know, but your sister
had some problems,

30:17.677 --> 30:18.946
and I can't leave you here,

30:18.946 --> 30:20.616
not with the way
they handled it.

30:20.616 --> 30:21.919
Wait.
I forgot.

30:21.919 --> 30:23.154
I have to get something
from the art room.

30:23.154 --> 30:24.357
Yeah, go ahead.

30:24.357 --> 30:26.995
[ children playing
and laughing ]

30:28.900 --> 30:31.839
BOY: Throw it!

30:31.839 --> 30:33.341
Go, go, go!

30:33.341 --> 30:34.712
Mm.

30:34.712 --> 30:36.147
Go to the car, honey.

30:36.147 --> 30:38.218
Actually, give me your phone
and then go to the car.

30:38.218 --> 30:39.554
Mm.

30:39.554 --> 30:41.659
[ down-tempo music plays ]

30:41.659 --> 30:47.002
♪♪♪♪

30:47.002 --> 30:49.742
Um, one minute.
One second.

30:49.742 --> 30:52.179
Um, Mr. Fleishman.

30:52.179 --> 30:54.584
Mr. Fleishman.
TOBY: Hey!

30:54.584 --> 30:55.920
One day, you will understand
the breadth

30:55.920 --> 30:57.824
of what a piece of shit
you are.

30:57.824 --> 30:58.893
And I hope I'm there
to see you

30:58.893 --> 31:00.395
when you realize
you're worthless.

31:00.395 --> 31:01.364
Um, Mr. Fleishman --

31:01.364 --> 31:02.968
It's Dr. Fleishman,
you dipshit.

31:02.968 --> 31:08.713
♪♪♪♪

31:08.713 --> 31:14.390
♪♪♪♪

31:14.390 --> 31:19.868
♪♪♪♪

31:19.868 --> 31:25.580
♪♪♪♪

31:25.580 --> 31:31.090
♪♪♪♪

31:31.090 --> 31:36.735
♪♪♪♪

31:36.735 --> 31:42.479
♪♪♪♪

31:47.890 --> 31:50.161
[ coin clinks ]

31:52.199 --> 31:54.604
[ can falls ]

31:54.604 --> 31:57.342
SOLLY: Are we going to
your or Mom's house?

31:57.342 --> 31:59.548
Um...

31:59.548 --> 32:02.353
Hey, guys, could I, um --
Can I talk to you for a second?

32:02.353 --> 32:03.690
Could we go sit down,
actually?

32:03.690 --> 32:04.858
What is it?

32:04.858 --> 32:07.430
Uh, well, it's --
it's your mother.

32:07.430 --> 32:09.033
I mean, she's fine.
She's fine.

32:09.033 --> 32:11.304
Or at least
I think she's fine.

32:11.304 --> 32:12.540
But, um --
No, it's fine.

32:12.540 --> 32:14.209
Here, come here,
come here, come here.

32:14.209 --> 32:18.251
But, um...well, she's having
some issues, okay?

32:18.251 --> 32:20.656
And she's taking some time
right now.

32:20.656 --> 32:22.125
Here, sit down.

32:22.125 --> 32:24.397
What --
What does that mean?

32:24.397 --> 32:26.267
Well, it means you'll be with me
full-time

32:26.267 --> 32:29.073
for the foreseeable future.

32:29.073 --> 32:31.712
W-What does that mean?

32:31.712 --> 32:33.516
Um...

32:33.516 --> 32:37.022
Your mother has decided
to, like,

32:37.022 --> 32:40.028
not be in our lives
so much.

32:40.028 --> 32:41.430
She's not
on a business trip.

32:41.430 --> 32:43.636
She, um...

32:43.636 --> 32:45.773
She, uh --
She dropped you off that day

32:45.773 --> 32:48.946
and she doesn't appear to be
coming back to pick you up.

32:48.946 --> 32:50.348
Mnh-mnh.
No.

32:50.348 --> 32:52.252
[ voice breaking ]
No, she wouldn't do that.

32:52.252 --> 32:53.622
No, I know
it seems impossible.

32:53.622 --> 32:56.762
I mean, no, it seems
that way to me, too.

32:56.762 --> 32:58.833
But I just, like --

32:58.833 --> 33:01.103
I don't know how to, like,
protect you from this.

33:01.103 --> 33:02.372
I tried.
I sent you to camp.

33:02.372 --> 33:04.711
I thought it would resolve,
but...

33:04.711 --> 33:07.149
I can't keep lying to you,
okay?

33:07.149 --> 33:10.756
[ crying ]

33:10.756 --> 33:12.894
LIBBY: The children reacted
the same way they did

33:12.894 --> 33:15.265
when they told them
about the divorce --

33:15.265 --> 33:18.972
with questions
about survival.

33:18.972 --> 33:21.444
He tried to answer honestly.

33:21.444 --> 33:23.983
Yes, you will probably
see her again.

33:23.983 --> 33:25.986
Yes, they'll manage.

33:25.986 --> 33:27.991
Yes, he's sorry.

33:27.991 --> 33:29.561
He's so sorry.

33:29.561 --> 33:33.869
♪♪♪♪

33:33.869 --> 33:38.445
♪♪♪♪

33:38.445 --> 33:42.820
♪♪♪♪

33:53.709 --> 33:56.314
SOLLY:
♪♪ Like a small boat ♪♪

33:56.314 --> 33:58.084
♪♪ In the ocean ♪♪

33:58.084 --> 34:00.689
♪♪ Sending big waves ♪♪

34:00.689 --> 34:03.094
♪♪ Into motion ♪♪

34:03.094 --> 34:05.198
BOTH:
♪♪ Like how a single word ♪♪

34:05.198 --> 34:08.104
♪♪ Can make a heart open ♪♪

34:08.104 --> 34:11.076
♪♪ I might only have one match ♪♪

34:11.076 --> 34:13.916
♪♪ But I can make an explosion ♪♪

34:13.916 --> 34:17.122
♪♪ All those things
I didn't say ♪♪

34:17.122 --> 34:19.894
♪♪ Wrecking balls
inside my brain ♪♪

34:19.894 --> 34:22.733
♪♪ I will scream them
loud tonight ♪♪

34:22.733 --> 34:25.572
♪♪ Can you hear my voice
this time? ♪♪

34:25.572 --> 34:28.444
♪♪ This is my fight song ♪♪

34:28.444 --> 34:31.351
♪♪ Take-back-my-life song ♪♪

34:31.351 --> 34:36.327
♪♪ Prove-I'm-all-right song ♪♪

34:36.895 --> 34:39.400
♪♪ My power's turned on ♪♪

34:39.400 --> 34:43.208
♪♪ Starting right now
I'll be strong ♪♪

34:43.208 --> 34:46.882
♪♪ I'll play my fight song ♪♪

34:46.882 --> 34:52.694
♪♪ And I don't really care
if nobody else believes ♪♪

34:52.694 --> 34:58.873
♪♪ 'Cause I've still got
a lot of fight left in me ♪♪

35:00.142 --> 35:05.819
♪♪ 'Cause I've still got
a lot of fight left in me ♪♪

35:06.655 --> 35:09.359
[ muffled television playing ]

35:09.359 --> 35:11.130
[ dog barking ]

35:11.130 --> 35:13.034
Wait.
You didn't.

35:13.034 --> 35:14.871
[ laughing ]
No way!

35:14.871 --> 35:15.974
Oh!

35:15.974 --> 35:17.777
Hi! Hi! Hi!

35:17.777 --> 35:19.013
Oh, my goodness!

35:19.013 --> 35:20.750
Hi! [ laughs ]

35:20.750 --> 35:23.856
You named him Bubbles,
didn't you?

35:23.856 --> 35:27.630
- Hi, Bubbles. Oh!
- Hi, Bubbles!

35:27.630 --> 35:29.834
- Oh, who's a good girl?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

35:29.834 --> 35:31.236
Oh!

35:35.513 --> 35:36.782
People always say to use
the pasta water,

35:36.782 --> 35:38.117
but I'm never sure
what that means.

35:38.117 --> 35:39.253
Like, when do you
put it in?

35:39.253 --> 35:40.723
I just put the sauce on.

35:40.723 --> 35:42.927
It smells really good.
My dad never makes pasta.

35:42.927 --> 35:44.063
SETH:
You doing okay?

35:44.063 --> 35:45.900
I'm better.

35:45.900 --> 35:48.104
VANESSA:
Okay, dinner!

35:48.104 --> 35:49.473
Mm. Great.

35:49.473 --> 35:50.909
May a pox break out
at this summer camp

35:50.909 --> 35:53.381
that's only ever outdone
by a concurrent plague

35:53.381 --> 35:56.087
of termites
and venereal disease.

35:56.087 --> 35:58.859
TOBY: Termites?
- Yes.

35:58.859 --> 36:00.395
SOLLY:
Can you pass the spaghetti?

36:00.395 --> 36:02.634
SETH: All right! Looks good.
TOBY: Thank you.

36:02.634 --> 36:05.371
You know, I knew your dad
when he was your age.

36:05.371 --> 36:08.077
He was very short.
And he was really fat.

36:08.077 --> 36:09.948
- I know.
- That's not nice.

36:09.948 --> 36:11.785
Yeah, you were still my friend,
though.

36:11.785 --> 36:13.421
SETH: I was.
VANESSA: We have salad, too.

36:13.421 --> 36:14.591
- Ah, that's great. Thank you.
SETH: Dry lettuce.

36:14.591 --> 36:16.460
Oh, yeah?
And there's no dressing?

36:16.460 --> 36:18.297
VANESSA: No dressing, no.
- Thank you.

36:18.297 --> 36:20.101
SOLLY: Did you guys really
meet at camp?

36:20.101 --> 36:21.337
SETH: Sure did.

36:21.337 --> 36:23.976
Your dad was very
into astronomy.

36:23.976 --> 36:25.378
Looks delicious.

36:25.378 --> 36:28.050
Get some pasta.
Eat up.

36:28.050 --> 36:30.422
It looks beautiful.
Could I -- could I tr--

36:30.422 --> 36:32.125
No, I'll just --
Pass?

36:32.125 --> 36:33.596
Yeah, sure.
Yes, please.

36:33.596 --> 36:35.633
SOLLY: Oh, this is really good.
SETH: Thank you.

36:35.633 --> 36:37.168
Really?

36:37.168 --> 36:39.039
Are you sure
you don't want some?

36:39.039 --> 36:41.879
[ indistinct conversation ]

36:41.879 --> 36:43.381
SOLLY:
Ooh, maggots.

36:43.381 --> 36:45.318
Oh, come on.

36:45.318 --> 36:47.089
Don't bring up maggots
while we're eating.

36:47.089 --> 36:49.160
This is very good,
Vanessa.

36:49.160 --> 36:51.197
VANESSA: Really?
HANNAH: Yeah.

36:51.197 --> 36:53.034
And then they were gone.

36:53.034 --> 36:56.742
And he could no longer pretend
what happened didn't happen.

36:56.742 --> 37:01.184
♪♪♪♪

37:01.184 --> 37:05.826
♪♪♪♪

37:05.826 --> 37:10.202
♪♪♪♪

37:10.202 --> 37:14.811
♪♪♪♪

37:14.811 --> 37:19.086
♪♪♪♪

37:19.086 --> 37:22.560
How could Hannah be these
two people, Toby wondered.

37:22.560 --> 37:24.698
She was a person who,
just a few hours ago,

37:24.698 --> 37:26.969
had a global humiliation,

37:26.969 --> 37:29.040
then learned that her mother
had abandoned her,

37:29.040 --> 37:31.712
and then, in a minute,
was on her knees,

37:31.712 --> 37:34.951
unmoored by her new puppy.

37:34.951 --> 37:38.291
For a few years, Hannah would
straddle being both people,

37:38.291 --> 37:39.861
and that was just the worst --

37:39.861 --> 37:42.199
both for her to endure
innocence

37:42.199 --> 37:44.170
and maturity in the same body

37:44.170 --> 37:47.175
and for him to watch
her innocence vanish

37:47.175 --> 37:49.013
in drips until it was gone.

37:49.013 --> 37:52.452
I have to run out for an errand
for a minute.

37:52.452 --> 37:56.227
Will you be okay if I --
if I leave here real quick?

37:56.227 --> 37:57.730
Mm-hmm.

37:57.730 --> 37:59.934
Okay.
Call me if you need me, okay?

38:03.374 --> 38:05.412
Growing up was disgusting.

38:05.412 --> 38:10.756
♪♪♪♪

38:10.756 --> 38:15.833
♪♪♪♪

38:15.833 --> 38:20.943
♪♪♪♪

38:20.943 --> 38:25.820
♪♪♪♪

38:25.820 --> 38:27.790
Long time, no see,
Dr. Fleishman.

38:27.790 --> 38:29.694
Is she up there?
She just got home.

38:29.694 --> 38:30.896
Should I tell her
you're coming?

38:30.896 --> 38:31.698
No, no, no, no.

38:31.698 --> 38:34.436
Uh, she's expecting me.

38:34.436 --> 38:36.307
[ elevator bell dings ]

38:36.307 --> 38:41.183
♪♪♪♪

38:41.183 --> 38:46.059
♪♪♪♪

38:56.347 --> 39:00.623
There was no confrontation
that would make this better.

39:00.623 --> 39:02.927
The decision was made.

39:02.927 --> 39:04.630
It was over.

39:13.013 --> 39:15.252
That weekend,
Toby, Hannah, and Solly

39:15.252 --> 39:18.458
embarked on their new life
as a family of three

39:18.458 --> 39:22.534
that was no longer waiting for
their former fourth to show up.

39:22.534 --> 39:24.871
Do you think it will
ever not be hot?

39:24.871 --> 39:27.041
Uh, like I said, you won't
always feel this way.

39:27.041 --> 39:28.678
Nothing lasts forever.

39:30.047 --> 39:31.651
But it wasn't all he was
thinking about right now.

39:31.651 --> 39:33.287
Look at that giant lizard.

39:33.287 --> 39:35.493
God help him, he was thinking
that he was so happy

39:35.493 --> 39:37.529
to not be alone anymore.

39:39.366 --> 39:42.507
He didn't want to make peace
with his loneliness.

39:42.507 --> 39:44.511
Let's go.
Come on.

39:44.511 --> 39:45.879
How's it so dark?

39:45.879 --> 39:47.650
It kind of freaked me out
when I first saw it,

39:47.650 --> 39:51.423
but I knew
you'd find it interesting.

39:51.423 --> 39:53.962
Now he didn't have to.

39:53.962 --> 39:55.733
You ready?

39:55.733 --> 39:58.304
Come on.
Okay.

39:58.304 --> 40:01.644
[ soft rumbling ]

40:23.454 --> 40:24.724
SOLLY:
I need to leave.

40:24.724 --> 40:27.329
We have to leave!

40:27.329 --> 40:30.134
Oh, hey, hey, hey.
Yo, Solly.

40:31.470 --> 40:33.007
Solly.

40:34.443 --> 40:36.446
Solly. Solly.

40:36.446 --> 40:38.284
Hey, Hannah, come on.

40:38.284 --> 40:40.021
[ Calum Scott and Tiesto's
"Dancing on My Own" plays ]

40:40.021 --> 40:44.162
♪♪ Somebody said you got
a new friend ♪♪

40:45.633 --> 40:47.369
HANNAH:
Solly, wait.

40:48.471 --> 40:53.114
♪♪ Does she love you better
than I can? ♪♪

40:53.114 --> 40:56.855
♪♪♪♪

40:56.855 --> 41:02.032
♪♪ And there's a big black sky
over my town ♪♪

41:02.032 --> 41:05.673
♪♪♪♪

41:05.673 --> 41:10.148
♪♪ I know where you're at,
I bet she's around ♪♪

41:10.148 --> 41:14.122
♪♪♪♪

41:14.122 --> 41:18.330
♪♪ And, yeah,
I know it's stupid ♪♪

41:18.330 --> 41:22.940
♪♪ But I just gotta see it
for myself ♪♪

41:22.940 --> 41:25.277
♪♪ I'm in the corner ♪♪

41:25.277 --> 41:27.349
♪♪ Watching you kiss her ♪♪

41:27.349 --> 41:29.185
♪♪ Oh, oh, oh ♪♪

41:31.057 --> 41:33.661
♪♪ And I'm right over here ♪♪

41:33.661 --> 41:35.666
♪♪ Why can't you see me? ♪♪

41:35.666 --> 41:37.936
♪♪ Oh, oh, oh ♪♪

41:39.641 --> 41:41.878
♪♪ And I'm giving it my all ♪♪

41:41.878 --> 41:46.655
♪♪ But I'm not the guy
you're taking home ♪♪

41:46.655 --> 41:48.659
♪♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪♪

41:48.659 --> 41:53.368
♪♪ I keep dancing on my own ♪♪

41:53.368 --> 41:55.772
♪♪ Oh ♪♪

41:55.772 --> 41:57.844
